        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3082979519" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18107496417853512824">4 stars<br/><br/>The ending of this one ripped out my soul and I can’t even. Nice mystery, as always, but Beauvoir’s story line is the true heart. <br/><br/><b>Setting:</b> ★★★★★<br/><b>Plot:</b> ★★★ 1/2<br/><b>Character arcs:</b> ★★★★★<br/><br/><i>The Beautiful Mystery</i> is the 8th installment in the Armand Gamache Canadian mystery series by writing goddess Louise Penny. I recommend skipping this review and checking out <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3074929892' rel='nofollow noopener'>Still Life</a> if you are at all interested in starting at the beginning of this series. <br/><br/>[This review spoils some plot points of the earlier book</span>
  <span id="freeText18107496417853512824" style="display:none">4 stars<br /><br />The ending of this one ripped out my soul and I can’t even. Nice mystery, as always, but Beauvoir’s story line is the true heart. <br /><br /><b>Setting:</b> ★★★★★<br /><b>Plot:</b> ★★★ 1/2<br /><b>Character arcs:</b> ★★★★★<br /><br /><i>The Beautiful Mystery</i> is the 8th installment in the Armand Gamache Canadian mystery series by writing goddess Louise Penny. I recommend skipping this review and checking out <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3074929892" rel="nofollow noopener">Still Life</a> if you are at all interested in starting at the beginning of this series. <br /><br />[This review spoils some plot points of the earlier books in order to talk about this one.]<br /><br />Armand Gamache and his second in command, Jean-Guy Beauvoir, find themselves in an incredibly unique situation. <b>A reclusive and previously secret community of Gilbertine monks have not only been discovered by the modern world, but the sins of the modern world have finally caught up to them—there's been a murder</b>. <br /><br />Gamache and Beauvoir are on the case. However, this time it's different. <br /><br /><b>The monks live in a castle-like monastery in the middle of the wilderness. They let no one in—under any circumstances. Until Gamache and Beauvoir.</b> Inducted into the aura of secrecy and faith entangled in the atmosphere, the two detectives soon find themselves at the heart of international intrigue, worldly concepts of faith versus the self, and the most primal of all crimes: the act of the murder. <br /><br />On top of this set up, Gamache and Beauvoir are still mentally healing from the deadly plant raid, and subsequent video leak, of a previous book. <b>Gamache is slowly healing, but Beauvoir is not</b>. <br /><br />He's cracking. <br /><br /><b>And this time, Gamache might not be able to save him</b>.<br /><br />I know I say this every time, but Louise Penny is a master at reader engagement. Once I start reading these books, I can't stop. I need to know what the characters will do next. It's not even the mystery plot—yes, it's interesting, and yes, I do want to know who murdered the victim—really, I just want to see what the characters are up to. This one was no exception. I loved it, I laughed, I cried, and at the end I was floored. <br /><br />Anyway, please read these books. They're amazing. <br /><br /><a href="https://www.amyimogenereads.com/" rel="nofollow noopener">Blog</a> | <a href="https://www.instagram.com/amyimogenereads/" rel="nofollow noopener">Instagram</a></span>
